Lady An has not written to me, nor sent your disgraceful doll’s-cap; I have heard nothing about the MacaireApparently someone trying to get help from the Ashburtons, so called by TC after Robert Macaire, a rogue made famous in Honoré Daumier’s cartoons (see 10:179TC to JWC, 15 Sept. 1838), or looking like the character in the play Robert Macaire (1834) by F. Lemaître and Benjamin Antier. since my pilgrimage to Greek Street months ago. Of course I am ready for any further adventure in that line: but I fear Macaire will have to enlist at last, if he has not already done so. If I could save her Ladyship a journey to Addiscombe in this damp weather by riding out as her substitute, and reporting upon Painters, rebuking them, or doing anything else, it would be very easy indeed, and perhaps a good work? But I suppose it won’t be accepted, after all.— “Charles Villiers, Hy Mildmay”:Charles Pelham Villiers (1802–98; ODNB
