Here we still are, and have to continue till Friday: “the Thackerays were coming,” the &c—in short, my Lady and Jane had settled that we could not go till the day after Newyearsday; and so in waiting for that date, still four days ahead of us remain for perfect idleness, indigestion, and smoking of tobacco under difficulties! The people are all very good to us, and intrinsically most of them are really agreeable and superior people: nevertheless one feels utterly out of place in such a scene of strenuous donothingism waited on by all the elegancies; and I shall be truly thankful, I for one, to get back to my own cell, and some kind of attempt at rational employment again.Edward FitzGerald wrote to a friend in Dec. and said that he had recently called on TC, who thought his visit to Malvern had done him “little good. He would be quite well, he says, if he threw his Books away, and walked about the mountains … . Nature made him a Writer: so he must wear himself out writing Lives of Sterling, etc., for the Benefit of the World” (Terhune, LEF 2:44).— Jane has quite got rid of her cold; I too, in spite of unwholesome hours and elements, contrive to swim along without running quite on the rocks; I ride, by myself, two hours, almost every day, and that is the circumstance that saves me. Our party for some time was very thin; it still consists only of Miss Farrer, Thackeray with his two little girls, Lady Sandwich (a good old cheery-hearted tho’ very weakly dame): and so, or nearly so, we expect it to continue till Friday, when it finally dissolves. Thy is just returned from lecturing and lionizing to the full extent in Edinr; he is not of great profit to talk with, but he is easy and agreeable, and his presence, taking away the burden of talk from the others, is so far very welcome. We have also a little Chemist called Bloxham, a
man not unlike Geo: Johnston of Glo’ster,Charles Loudon Bloxam (1831–87), analytic chemist, 24 Duke St., Grosvenor Sq., who taught in various London institutions and was a prof. of practical chemistry, 1856–70, and of chemistry, 1870–87. Dr. George Johnston. only he is London-bred and very finished in his manner; who is galloping thro’ some kind of “course” with Lord A. in a certain “laboratory” out of doors: poor little fellow, I daresay he is much struck with the strange modes of “study,” among other things, whh are prevalent here!Thackeray wrote to Lady Stanley, 28 Dec.: “My children & I are on a little visit here and the young ones enjoy their first visit to a great house, where everybody is as kind as kind can be— Only the Carlyles & Lady Sandwich here, and a chemist who teaches his art to Lord Ashburton in a private room where they have furnaces and awful experiments” (Ray 2:824). Palmerston’s fall with the continual London gossip on it, gives rise to much talk in our sphere;The Queen had long been dissatisfied with the foreign minister, Lord Palmerston, not least because of his ignoring royal suggestions and advice. She had a year earlier drawn up a memorandum demanding that she be kept fully informed and that once she had approved a measure, it should not be arbitrarily altered. Palmerston promised to mend his ways, yet disagreements remained over the attack on Gen. Haynau (see 25:203 JWC to TC, 8 Sept. 1850
) and his intention of welcoming Kossuth. Then he at once approved of Louis Napoleon’s coup d’état, 2 Dec., whereas the cabinet, adopting the Queen’s attitude, instructed the British ambassador in Paris, 5 Dec., to carry on as though nothing had happened, passing no judgment on the affair. The resulting embarrassment forced Palmerston’s resignation, 19 Dec., and he was replaced by Lord Granville. Louis Napoleon do do:—Eheu!
